## 2. Limitations of the Current oref Approach

### 2.1 Reactive, Not Predictive

oref responds to BG that is already moving. By the time a postprandial rise is detected and SMBs begin firing, the BG excursion is already in progress. Insulin has a 15–20 minute onset even with fast-acting analogs (Lyumjev, Fiasp), meaning a reactive response always chases the meal curve rather than anticipating it.

### 2.2 Linear Carb Absorption Assumption

When a user enters carbs, oref absorbs them at a configurable fixed rate (default ~30 g/hr, adjustable). Real meals are not linear. A bowl of oatmeal with butter absorbs very differently from white rice, and both absorb differently from a protein bar. The fat-protein effect, gastric emptying variation, and meal composition all shape the absorption curve in ways the current model cannot represent.

### 2.3 No Macro Awareness

oref sees “60 grams of carbohydrates.” It does not know:

- Whether those carbs are simple or complex
- Whether they were accompanied by 40g of fat that will slow gastric emptying
- Whether 30g of protein will trigger hepatic gluconeogenesis 2–4 hours later

This leads to the classic T1D experience: good BG at 2 hours post-meal, high BG at 4–5 hours post-meal. The protein and fat tail is essentially invisible to oref.

### 2.4 No Physiological State Awareness

oref has no knowledge of:

- How much the user slept or sleep quality
- Whether the user exercised yesterday or today
- Whether the user is in a state of physiological stress (high cortisol, illness)
- Whether the user’s body is currently glycogen-depleted from endurance activity

All of these dramatically affect insulin sensitivity, yet the algorithm uses the same ISF and CR regardless.

### 2.5 No Learning Over Time

oref does not improve with use. A user who has been looping for 3 years has the same algorithm quality as one who started last week, assuming identical settings. All the historical data generated — thousands of BG readings, hundreds of meal responses, dozens of exercise sessions — is discarded after it is used for real-time control. It is never fed back to improve the model.

### 2.6 Binary Meal Entry

The current user interaction model is: enter carbs, or don’t. UAM provides a crude fallback for forgetting, but there is no middle ground — no way to communicate meal composition, timing, or confidence. The proposed system fundamentally changes this by using Cronometer macro data to give the algorithm a rich, pre-meal physiological forecast.

