## 11. Implementation Roadmap

The following phases represent a logical development sequence from current state to the full proposed system. Each phase builds on the previous and provides value independently.

### Phase 1: Signal Enhancement (Foundation)

**Goal:** Improve the quality of signals fed into oref without changing the core dosing logic.

- Implement Kalman filter on CGM readings
- Calculate and log BG velocity, acceleration, jerk (for analysis, not yet used in dosing)
- Implement BG residual calculation (actual vs. IOB-expected)
- Normalize Garmin HRV and resting HR to personal Z-scores each morning
- Log all data to a local time-series store for retrospective analysis

**Value delivered:** Better insight data; foundation for all subsequent phases. No change to dosing behavior yet, so minimal risk.

-----

### Phase 2: Macro-Aware Meal Model

**Goal:** Replace oref’s linear carb absorption with the composite macronutrient model.

- Build the composite absorption curve from Cronometer macro data
- Implement fiber adjustment to effective carbs
- Implement Bayesian absorption estimator (replacing fixed linear absorption)
- Add fat-protein tail prediction and schedule delayed basal/SMB response
- Log predicted vs. actual curves for validation

**Value delivered:** Significantly improved postprandial control, especially for high-fat and high-protein meals. Addresses the “great at 2 hours, high at 4 hours” problem.

-----

### Phase 3: Daily State Vector and Static Modifiers

**Goal:** Incorporate Garmin recovery and sleep data into daily ISF/CR modifications.

- Build morning state vector calculation from overnight Garmin sync
- Implement HRV Z-score to ISF modifier mapping
- Implement sleep quality to ISF and basal modifier mapping
- Apply daily modifiers to oref parameter inputs
- Add user-facing explanation in Trio UI (“Your sensitivity is adjusted today because…”)

**Value delivered:** Algorithm adapts to the user’s physiological state day to day. Reduces unexplained BG variability caused by sleep and stress.

-----

### Phase 4: Post-Exercise Sensitivity Modeling

**Goal:** Apply post-exercise ISF and CR modifiers based on saved Garmin workout data.

- Implement workout classification and intensity scoring
- Build post-exercise sensitivity decay curves by workout type
- Apply time-decaying ISF modifier from workout completion time
- Implement glycogen depletion estimation and post-workout CR modifier
- Add UI indicator for active post-exercise sensitivity window

**Value delivered:** Elimination of the most common post-exercise hypoglycemia cause (over-bolusing for post-workout meals); better overnight BG after exercise days.

-----

### Phase 5: Adaptive Learning

**Goal:** Implement retrospective learning to personalize all coefficients.

- Implement meal retrospective analysis pipeline
- EWMA coefficient updating for carb absorption speed, protein sensitivity, fat delay
- Outlier detection and flagging
- Diurnal ISF/CR curve learning
- User dashboard for reviewing learning history and flagging anomalies

**Value delivered:** System improves continuously with use. Personalization that no static algorithm can match.

-----

### Phase 6: Live Heart Rate (Optional Enhancement)

**Goal:** Add real-time HR to enable in-activity algorithm adaptation.

- Validate Garmin BLE HR advertisement (or build Connect IQ app)
- Implement iOS BLE HR receiver
- Integrate live HR into zone classifier
- Apply in-activity ISF suppression (Zone 3+ exercise)
- Apply incidental activity (Zone 1 elevation) mild modifier
- Enable real-time post-exercise window triggering

**Value delivered:** Algorithm adapts in real time to current physical state, not just historical workout data. Closes the last major temporal gap.

